nsive Player of the Year]] ({{nbay|2007|end}})\n* 9\u00d7 [[NBA All-Defensive Team|NBA All-Defensive First Team]] ({{nbay|1999|end}}\u2013{{nbay|2004|end}}, {{nbay|2007|end}}, {{nbay|2008|end}}, {{nbay|2010|end}})\n* 3\u00d7 [[NBA All-Defensive Team|NBA All-Defensive Second Team]] ({{nbay|2005|end}}, {{nbay|2006|end}}, {{nbay|2011|end}})\n* [[NBA All-Rookie Second Team]] ({{nbay|1995|end}})\n* 4\u00d7 [[List of National Basketball Association annual rebounding leaders|NBA rebounding champion]] ({{nbay|2003|end}}\u2013{{nbay|2006|end}})\n* [[J. Walter Kennedy Citizenship Award]] ({{nbay|2005|end}})\n* [[Mr. Basketball USA]] (1995)\n* [[McDonald's All-American Game]] MVP ([[1995 McDonald's All-American Boys Game|1995]])\n* 2\u00d7 First-team [[Parade All-America Boys Basketball Team|''Parade'' All-American]] (1994, 1995)\n* [[Illinois Mr. Basketball]] (1995)\n| stat1label   = [[Point (basketball)|Points]]\n| stat1value   = 26,071 (17.8 ppg)\n| stat2label   = [[Rebound (basketball)|Rebounds]]\n| stat2value   = 14,662 (10.0 rpg)\n| stat3label   = [[Assist (basketball)|Assists]]\n| stat3value   = 5,445 (3.7 apg)\n| nba_profile  = kevin_garnett\n| bbr          = garneke01\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalSport|Men's [[basketball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{flagu|United States}}}}\n{{MedalOlympic}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2000 Summer Olympics|2000 Sydney]] | [[Basketball at the 2000 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's tournament|Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA Americas Championship]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[FIBA Americas Championship 1999|1999 San Juan]] | [[United States men's national basketball team|Team]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Kevin Maurice Garnett''' (born May 19, 1976) is an American former professional [[basketball]] player who played for 21 seasons in the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA). Known for his intensity, defensive ability, and versatility, Garnett is considered one of the greatest [[Power forward (basketball)|power forwards]] of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com/nba/gallery/ranking-the-25-greatest-players-in-nba-history-100716|title=Ranking the 25 greatest players in NBA history|publisher=FOX Sports|date=October 20, 2017|accessdate=March 7, 2019}}</ref> He is one of four NBA players to win both the [[NBA Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player]] and the [[NBA Defensive Player of the Year Award|Defensive Player of the Year]] awards.{{refn|group=\"n\"|[[David Robinson (basketball)|David Robinson]], [[Michael Jordan]] and [[Hakeem Olajuwon]] are the other three.}} In high school, Garnett was a 1995 [[McDonald's All-American]] at [[Farragut Career Academy]] and won a national player of the year award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/playoffs/2010/columns/story?page=beforetheywerestars-garnett-100608 |title=Before they were stars: Boston Celtics' Kevin Garnett |publisher=ESPN |date=June 8, 2010 |accessdate=December 29, 2010}}</ref><ref name=mcdonalds>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/hawks/news/wilkins-honored-one-35-greatest-mcdonalds-all-americans |title=Wilkins Honored as One of 35 Greatest McDonald's All Americans |publisher=NBA|date=January 31, 2012 |accessdate=February 9, 2012}}</ref> He entered the [[1995 NBA draft]], where he was selected with the fifth overall pick by the [[Minnesota Timberwolves]] and became the first NBA player drafted [[NBA high school players|directly out of high school]] in [[1975 NBA draft|20 years]].\n\nGarnett made an immediate impact with the Minnesota Timberwolves, leading them to eight consecutive [[NBA Playoffs|playoff]] appearances. In 2004, he led the Timberwolves to the [[NBA Conference Finals|Western Conference Finals]] and won the NBA MVP Award. Garnett has been named to 15 [[NBA All-Star Game|All-Star Game]]s, winning the [[NBA All-Star Game Most Valuable Player Award|All-Star MVP award]] in [[2003 NBA All-Star Game|2003]], and is currently tied for third-most [[List of NBA All-Stars|All-Star selections]] with 15.{{refn|group=\"n\"|Garnett is tied with [[Shaquille O'Neal]] and [[Tim Duncan]]. They trail [[Kobe Bryant]] (17 selections) and [[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar]] (19).}} He was named the [[NBA Defensive Player of the Year Award|NBA Defensive Player of the Year]] in [[2007\u201308 NBA season|2007\u201308]], and has been selected nine times for [[All-NBA Team]]s and 12 times for [[NBA All-Defensive Team|All-Defensive Teams]].<ref name=\"stats\">{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/g/garneke01.html |title=Kevin Garnett Statistics |work=Basketball-reference.com |date= |accessdate=October 27, 2008}}</ref> Garnett also holds several Timberwolves [[Franchise player|franchise]] records. He is known as \"'''the Big Ticket'''\" for his emphatic dunking and athleticism.\n\nIn 2007, after 12 seasons with the Timberwolves, Garnett joined the [[Boston Celtics]] in a blockbuster trade. In his first year with the Celtics, he helped lead them to the [[2008 NBA Finals|NBA championship]], while also finishing in third place for the [[NBA Most Valuable Player Award|MVP]] award.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/news/kobe_mvp_080506.html |title=NBA.com - Kobe Bryant Wins Most Valuable Player Award<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=May 30, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401110138/http://www.nba.com/news/kobe_mvp_080506.html |archive-date=April 1, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2013, Garnett was included in a second headline trade that sent him to the [[Brooklyn Nets]] with longtime Celtic [[Paul Pierce]]. In 2015, Garnett was traded back to Minnesota. He announced his retirement from professional basketball in September 2016. Garnett made his feature film debut, playing a fictionalized version of himself, in the 2019 film ''[[Uncut Gems]]''.\n\n==Early life and high school career==\nGarnett was born on May 19, 1976 in [[Greenville, South Carolina]], to Shirley Garnett. He was the second of his mother's three children.<ref name=\"fsnbio\">{{cite video|people=Frank Sinton, Steven Michaels (executive producers)|date=2003|title=[[Beyond the Glory]]|medium=Television production|publisher=[[Fox Sports Network]]}}</ref> Garnett's mother never married his father, O'Lewis McCullough, with their relationship ending shortly after his birth. Garnett grew up with his mother and stepfather, Ernest Irby, with whom he did not get along, and two sisters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/classic/biography/s/Garnett_Kevin.html|title='Da Kid' progressed quickly|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=January 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nGarnett fell in love with the sport of basketball while attending Hillcrest Middle School, although he did not play organized basketball until high school. In his first three years of high school, Garnett attended [[Mauldin High School]] in [[Mauldin, South Carolina]] and played on the school's basketball team. However, during the summer before his senior year of high school, Garnett was in the general vicinity of a fight between black and white students. Although not directly involved, Garnett was one of three students arrested for second-degree [[lynching]], a charge that was expunged through a pre-trial intervention.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0rzoMnXOPJI |title=Beyond the Glory \u2013 Kevin Garnett part 4 |publisher=YouTube.com |date=August 24, 2007 |accessdate=April 20, 2012}}</ref> Due to the racially charged incident and fearful of being a target, Garnett decided to leave Mauldin High<ref name=\"jockbio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jockbio.com/Bios/Garnett/Garnett_bio.html |title=JockBio: Kevin Garnett Biography |publisher=Jockbio.com |date= |accessdate=October 27, 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100512162711/http://www.jockbio.com/Bios/Garnett/Garnett_bio.html |archive-date=May 12, 2010 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> and transferred to [[Farragut Career Academy]] in [[Chicago]]'s West Side, for his senior year of high school.\n\nLiving with his sister in Chicago, Garnett led Farragut to a 28\u20132 record and was named National High School Player of the Year by ''[[USA Today]]''. He was also named [[Illinois Mr. Basketball|Mr. Basketball]] for the state of Illinois after averaging 25.2 points, 17.9 rebounds, 6.7 assists and 6.5 blocks while shooting 66.8% from the field. In four years of high school, Garnett posted an impressive 2,553 points, 1,809 rebounds and 737 blocked shots. In high school, Garnett played alongside [[Ronnie Fields]], who also became a professional basketball player. Garnett was named the Most Outstanding Player at the [[1995 McDonald's All-American Boys Game|McDonald's All-American Game]] after registering 18 points, 11 rebounds, 4 assists and 3 blocked shots, and then declared himself eligible for the [[1995 NBA draft]].<ref name=\"nbabio\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/playerfile/kevin_garnett/bio/ |title=Kevin Garnett Stats, Video, Bio, Profile |work=NBA.com |accessdate=December 20, 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151209082536/http://www.nba.com/playerfile/kevin_garnett/bio/ |archivedate=December 9, 2015}}</ref> To mark the 35th anniversary of the McDonald's All-American High School Boys Basketball Game, Garnett was honored as one of 35 Greatest McDonald's All-Americans.<ref name=\"mcdonalds\" /> Garnett's decision not to play [[college basketball]] was influenced in part by his failure to score well enough on the [[ACT (test)|ACT]] to meet [[NCAA]] requirements for freshman eligibility.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Farber|first1=Michael|title=Feel the Warmth the Timberwolves' Twin Wunderkinds, Kevin Garnett and Stephon Marbury, Have Built what Minnesota Hopes Is a Lasting Bond|url=https://www.si.com/vault/1997/01/20/221576/feel-the-warmth-the-timberwolves-twin-wunderkinds-kevin-garnett-and-stephon-marbury-have-built-what-minnesota-hopes-is-a-lasting-bond|accessdate=February 28, 2017|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=January 20, 1997}}</ref> Garnett told ''Student Sports Magazine'' in 1995 that if he had attended college he would have chosen to play college basketball for the [[Maryland Terrapins men's basketball|University of Maryland]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hudson|first1=John W.|title=Ignored and Ignited: H.o.o.p.s of Life|date=2007|publisher=[[AuthorHouse]]|isbn=9781434327079|page=145|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Zv3g-AYoXDIC&pg=PA145&lpg=PA145&dq=kevin+garnett+michigan+maryland&source=bl&ots=q2KlAVbv1Q&sig=kpna323n7-8buPJOwK1o7i7e8ys&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjdwpn0hLTSAhVFLcAKHb9uBS84FBDoAQgtMAM#v=onepage&q=kevin%20garnett%20michigan%20maryland&f=false|accessdate=March 1, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nA Chicago area high school coach referred Garnett with Eric Fleisher, then agent for 18 NBA players and son of first [[National Basketball Players Association]] head [[Larry Fleisher]], to discuss the possibility of going to the NBA straight out of high school. Two weeks later at the Lakeshore Athletic Club, Fleisher ran a small tryout where Garnett dominated against older, more-experienced competition. Fleisher then set [[Detroit Pistons]] assistant [[John Hammond (basketball)|John Hammond]] to run the drills at another workout at the [[University of Illinois-Chicago]] to gauge NBA interest. Representatives from the 13 teams with lottery picks, with [[Kevin McHale (basketball)|Kevin McHale]], [[Elgin Baylor]], [[Flip Saunders]], and [[Kevin Loughery]] among them, were in the workout that was scheduled around the same time as a pre-draft tryout camp. The workout included Garnett touching the box painted on the backboard above the rim multiple times, and McHale giving Garnett tips on shooting jump shots. An hour before going to the 1995 NBA Draft in the [[Toronto SkyDome]], his coach at Farragut, William (Wolf) Nelson, gave encouragement and told Garnett that he passed the last SAT test he took with a score of 970.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.si.com/nba/2015/02/24/kevin-garnett-minnesota-timberwolves-the-kid-flip-saunders-kevin-mchale|title=Kevin Garnett: The Kid who changed the game|first=Leigh|last=Montville|website=Sports Illustrated}}</ref><ref name=\"sportsonearth1\">{{Cite journal|url=http://www.sportsonearth.com/article/40114908/boston-celtics-center-kevin-garnett-is-older-and-richer-but-just-as-wise-as-ever|title=Kevin Garnett is older and richer but just as wise.|first=Leigh|last=Montville|date=October 29, 2012|via=www.sportsonearth.com}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===Minnesota Timberwolves (1995\u20132007)===\n\n====Early years (1995\u20131997)====\nGarnett was drafted with the fifth overall pick in the [[1995 NBA draft]] by the [[Minnesota Timberwolves]], and became the first player to be drafted directly out of high school since [[1975 NBA draft|1975]].<ref>\"[http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=KC&p_theme=kc&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EAF41BA06AEF878&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM From preps to the pros: High school senior Garnett enters NBA draft]\". Star News Services. May 12, 2005. Retrieved on February 22, 2009.</ref> Since joining the NBA for the 1989\u201390 season, the Timberwolves had not won more than 29 games in any season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.databasebasketball.com/teams/teampage.htm?tm=min&lg=n |title=Minnesota Timberwolves (1989 \u2013 ) Stats, History, Awards and More |publisher=Databasebasketball.com |date= |accessdate=October 27, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081006054531/http://www.databasebasketball.com/teams/teampage.htm?tm=min&lg=n |archivedate=October 6, 2008}}</ref> In Garnett's rookie season, the Timberwolves were in the midst of a transition phase; they replaced [[Bill Blair (basketball)|Bill Blair]] with [[Flip Saunders]] as head coach early in the season, and made several trades. Garnett initially came off the bench in his rookie year, but moved into the [[starting lineup]] soon after Saunders became head coach and with the urging of [[Sam Mitchell (basketball)|Sam Mitchell]]. In the final 42 games of the year, averaged 14 points, 8.4 rebounds and 2.26 blocks as a starter.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/> \nIn his rookie year, Garnett and fellow newcomer [[Tom Gugliotta]] carried the scoring load. Garnett did not immediately leap to stardom as later [[prep-to-pro]] prospects such as [[Amar'e Stoudemire]], [[LeBron James]] and [[Dwight Howard]] would, but he did have a very respectable rookie year. He was voted to the All-Rookie Second Team on averages of 10.4 points, 6.3 rebounds and 1.8 assists per game.<ref name=\"stats\" /> Despite having some promising players, the Timberwolves suffered through their seventh consecutive sub-30 win season and failed to make the playoffs. At the time, Garnett was the youngest NBA player in history at 19 years and 11 months of age.<ref name=\"nbabio\"/>\n\nBefore the [[1996\u201397 NBA season|1996\u201397 season]], the Timberwolves made a draft-day trade for [[point guard]] [[Stephon Marbury]] of the [[Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets men's basketball|Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets]]. During the season, Garnett posted improved averages of 17.0 points, 8.0 rebounds, 3.1 assists, 2.1 blocks and 1.7 steals.<ref name=\"stats\" /> He also had two games where he registered eight blocks.<ref name=\"nbabio\"/> With a 40\u201342 record, the Timberwolves made their first playoff appearance in franchise history, Garnett and Gugliotta made their first All-Star appearances, and Marbury established himself as a valuable young lead guard. However, the [[Houston Rockets]], led by [[Hakeem Olajuwon]], [[Clyde Drexler]], and [[Charles Barkley]], proved to be too much as the Timberwolves were swept 3\u20130 in the first round of the [[1997 NBA Playoffs]].\n\n====Franchise player (1997\u20132001)====\nIn August 1997, Garnett and Fleisher turned down the Timberwolves' offer of a contract worth $102 million over six years. They thought there would be more offered to them on the basis of the signings of $105 million over seven years for Alonzo Mourning of the Miami Heat and $100.8 million over seven years for Juwan Howard with the Washington Bullets. To get out of the spotlight while negotiations were ongoing, Garnett stayed in Fleisher's Westchester County home, north of New York City. One hour before the deadline on 1 October 1997,<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/> the Timberwolves and Garnett agreed on a six-year contract extension that was worth an unparalleled $126 million.<ref name=\"nbabio\"/> The contract was considered a risky move and many analysts speculated that the deal would make it impossible for the Wolves to sign new players or even keep their own. The enormous size of Garnett's contract was considered, by numerous sports writers, a major cause of labor tensions between players and owners that led to a lockout which shortened the [[1998\u201399 NBA season]]. Despite the furor over his new contract, Garnett continued to improve, averaging 18.5 points, 9.6 rebounds, 4.2 assists, 1.8 blocks, and 1.7 steals per game. Again, he was an All-Star, and the Timberwolves finished with their first winning record in franchise history (45\u201337 for the season). For the second consecutive year, the young Timberwolves bowed out of the playoffs in the first round, this time losing 3\u20132 to the [[Seattle SuperSonics]] and superstar point guard [[Gary Payton]]. The two wins against the Sonics marked the Wolves' first-ever playoff game wins. The off-season started poorly for the Timberwolves though as 20-point per game scorer [[Tom Gugliotta]] left for the [[Phoenix Suns]].\n\n[[File:Kevin Garnett with the Minnesota Timberwolves dunking, 2007.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Garnett as a member of the [[Minnesota Timberwolves]] (2007)]]\nIn the lockout-shortened [[1998\u201399 NBA season|season that followed]], Garnett broke through as a superstar. Putting up stats of 20.8 points, 10.4 rebounds, 4.3 assists and 1.8 blocks per game,<ref name=\"stats\" /> he was named to the All-NBA Third Team. However, midway through the season, [[Stephon Marbury]] was traded to the [[New Jersey Nets]]. Although the Wolves received two-time All-Star [[Terrell Brandon]] in return, they were not able to overcome the discord and limped into the playoffs as the eighth seed with a 25\u201325 record. The Wolves were defeated in the first round again, this time losing 3\u20131 to the eventual champion [[San Antonio Spurs]] who were led by young superstar and eventual [[NBA Finals MVP]] [[Tim Duncan]]. In the [[1999\u20132000 NBA season]], Garnett continued his notable play, averaging 22.9 points, 11.8 rebounds, 5.0 assists, 1.6 blocks and 1.5 steals per game. Garnett also made the first of his four All-NBA First Team appearances and came in second place in the MVP voting.<ref name=\"stats\" /> Assisted by sharpshooting rookie forward [[Wally Szczerbiak]] and steady veteran [[Terrell Brandon]], the Wolves posted a franchise-best 50\u201332 record, but succumbed in the first round to the [[Portland Trail Blazers]] 3\u20131.\n\nOn May 20, 2000, Timberwolves' guard and Garnett's close friend [[Malik Sealy]] was killed by a [[Drunk driving (United States)|drunk driver]] shortly after celebrating Garnett's 24th birthday.<ref>[http://static.espn.go.com/nba/news/2000/0520/541964.html Sealy dies in collision with pickup truck], May 22, 2000</ref> Later that year, the NBA ruled that the free agent signing of [[Joe Smith (basketball)|Joe Smith]] was illegal. The league punished the team for the illegal signing by stripping them of three first-round draft picks, fining [[Glen Taylor]] (the owner of the team) [[$]]3.5 million, and banning [[general manager]] [[Kevin McHale (basketball)|Kevin McHale]] for one year. In the [[2000\u201301 NBA season]], Garnett led the Wolves to a 47\u201335 record and made the All-NBA Second Team, but again, the Wolves did not survive the first round of the playoffs, losing to the Spurs 3\u20131.\n\n====MVP and division champions (2001\u20132004)====\nIn the [[2001\u201302 NBA season|2001\u201302 season]], Garnett posted another notable season, his averages of 21.2 points, 12.1 rebounds, 5.2 assists, 1.6 blocks and 1.2 steals per game enough for another All-NBA Second Team nomination. However, the Timberwolves bowed out in the first round for the sixth consecutive time, this time getting swept 3\u20130 by the [[Dallas Mavericks]] led by [[Michael Finley]], [[Steve Nash]] and [[Dirk Nowitzki]]. Garnett's [[2002\u201303 NBA season|next season]] was one of the best of his career, his 23.0 ppg / 13.4 rpg / 6.0 apg / 1.6 bpg / 1.4 spg season earning him his second All-NBA First Team nomination and second place in the MVP voting.<ref name=\"nbabio\"/> The Timberwolves posted a good 51\u201331 record, but for the seventh consecutive time, they did not make it out of the first round, this time losing to the [[Los Angeles Lakers]] 4\u20132.\n\nIn the [[2003\u201304 NBA season|2003\u201304 season]], things finally seemed to come together for Garnett. In past years, the Wolves had practically been a one-man show, but now, the Timberwolves had made two valuable acquisitions: highly talented but volatile swingman [[Latrell Sprewell]] and the seasoned two-time NBA champion [[Sam Cassell]], who supplanted [[Troy Hudson]] at [[point guard]]. In addition, defensive center [[Ervin Johnson]] complemented the inconsistent [[Michael Olowokandi]]. Powered by the best supporting cast up to this point in his career, Garnett averaged 24.2 points, 13.9 rebounds, 5.0 assists, 2.2 blocks and 1.5 steals per game for the season. Having recorded career-highs in points, rebounds, blocks and leading the league rebounds, Garnett was named the league [[NBA Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player]] for the first time in his career.<ref name=\"stats\" /> With a franchise-record 58 wins, the Wolves stormed into the playoffs, and finally conquered their playoff bane by defeating the [[Denver Nuggets]] 4\u20131 in the first round. After disposing of the strong [[Sacramento Kings]] 4\u20133 in the Western Conference semi-finals, Garnett and the Timberwolves met the Lakers in the Western Conference Finals. There, playmaker Cassell went down with a back injury. With reserve point guard Hudson also injured, the Timberwolves alternated between third playmaker [[Darrick Martin]] and shooting guard [[Fred Hoiberg]] at the \"one\", or even running Garnett himself as [[point forward]] or a real point guard. The [[Los Angeles Lakers]] pulled off a 4\u20132 victory in the series.\n\n====Frustration (2004\u20132007)====\nIn the [[2004\u201305 NBA season|2004\u201305 season]], Garnett was able to record a career-high in terms of scoring as he scored 47 points and grabbed 17 rebounds in a 115-122 loss to the Phoenix Suns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/boxscores/200501040MIN.html|title=Phoenix Suns at Minnesota Timberwolves Box Score, January 4, 2005|publisher=Basketball Reference|date=January 4, 2005|accessdate=January 17, 2020}}</ref> He was also named to the All-NBA Second Team,<ref name=\"stats\" /> but the Timberwolves failed to make the playoffs for the first time in eight years with a record of 44\u201338. The [[2005\u201306 NBA season|2005\u201306 season]] brought more frustration for Garnett. Sprewell turned down a three-year, $21 million extension, and the Wolves wary of his injuries and age, traded [[Sam Cassell|Cassell]] for the much less effective [[Marko Jari\u0107]], and the team's record for 2005\u201306 fell to 33\u201349. Despite Garnett's play, the team logged the second worst record since Garnett joined the franchise. Garnett subsequently earned All-NBA Third Team honors.\n\nDuring the 2007 off-season, Glen Taylor admitted that although he had planned on retaining Garnett, he would finally listen to trade offers.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.startribune.com/507/story/1261571.html |title=Sid Hartman, June 21: KG traded? Taylor says don't bet on it |publisher=Startribune.com |author=Sid Hartman, Star Tribune |date=June 25, 2007 |accessdate=October 27, 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013120737/http://www.startribune.com/507/story/1261571.html |archivedate=October 13, 2007}}</ref> Garnett's name was mentioned in various trade rumors involving the [[Chicago Bulls]], [[Los Angeles Lakers]], [[Golden State Warriors]], [[Indiana Pacers]], [[Boston Celtics]], [[Phoenix Suns]] and [[Dallas Mavericks]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=2912075 |title=Wolves-Celtics trade talk? Garnett says forget it |work=ESPN.com |last=Stein | first=Marc |date=June 23, 2007|accessdate=January 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Berger |first=Ken |url=http://www.newsday.com/sports/basketball/ny-spkobe0626,0,4957812.story?coll=ny-sports-headlines |title=Garnett-to-Lakers talk buzzes around NBA |work=NewsDay.com |date=June 25, 2007 |accessdate=January 6, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070630005701/http://www.newsday.com/sports/basketball/ny-spkobe0626%2C0%2C4957812.story?coll=ny-sports-headlines |archivedate=June 30, 2007}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://realgm.com/src_wiretap_archives/46747/20070627/phoenix_atlanta_minnesota_three_way_close/ |title=Phoenix, Atlanta, Minnesota Three-Way Close? |work=RealGM.com |date=June 27, 2007 |accessdate=January 6, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070629115251/http://realgm.com/src_wiretap_archives/46747/20070627/phoenix_atlanta_minnesota_three_way_close/ |archivedate=June 29, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Kawakami |first=Tim |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2007/06/29/kawakami-warriors-will-wright-move-lead-to-garnett/ |title=Kawakami: Warriors: Will Wright move lead to Garnett? |work=Mercury News |date=June 29, 2007 |accessdate=17 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Boston Celtics (2007\u20132013)===\n[[Image:Kevin Garnett.jpg|thumb|upright|Garnett in Game 4 of the [[2008 NBA Playoffs]] against the [[Atlanta Hawks]].]]\n[[Image:KG with a Massive Dunk.jpg|thumb|right|Garnett dunking a ball in a game against the [[Washington Wizards]].]]\nOn July 31, 2007, [[n:NBA: Minnesota ready to trade Kevin Garnett to Boston|Garnett was traded to the Boston Celtics]] in exchange for [[Al Jefferson]], [[Ryan Gomes]], [[Sebastian Telfair]], [[Gerald Green]], [[Theo Ratliff]], cash considerations, Boston's 2009 first-round draft pick (top 3 protected), and the [[Wayne Ellington|2009 first-round pick]] which Minnesota had traded to Boston in the [[Ricky Davis]]&ndash;[[Wally Szczerbiak]] trade of 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/celtics/news/press073107-garnett.html |title=Celtics Acquire 10-Time All-Star Kevin Garnett &#124; Celtics.com |publisher=Nba.com |date= |accessdate=October 27, 2008}}</ref> The 7-for-1 deal constitutes the largest number of players traded for a single player in league history.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=nba&id=2956104 Celtics obtain former MVP in 7-for-1 deal] July 31, 2007</ref> At the time of the trade, Garnett had the longest current tenure of any player in the NBA with one team, having played for the Timberwolves for his first 12 seasons (a total of 927 games). Garnett said that he was proud to be a part of the Celtics, and hoped to continue its proud tradition and basketball success.<ref>{{cite web|author=Marc Stein |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=2954127 |title=Sources: Celtics, Wolves agree to Garnett megadeal |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=July 31, 2007 |accessdate=April 20, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/20029788/ |title=KG says Celtics his best shot at a ring|publisher=MSNBC |date=July 31, 2007 |accessdate=April 20, 2012}}{{dead link|date=November 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref><ref>[http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2007/basketball/nba/wires/07/30/2030.ap.bkn.celtics.garnett.trade.0159/ Celtics, Minnesota Timberwolves agree to send Garnett to Boston]{{Dead link|date=August 2010|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref> On the day the trade was announced, Garnett signed a three-year, $60 million contract extension that would start after his prior deal ran out in 2009. On August 1, the day after signing with the Celtics, Garnett threw the ceremonial first pitch at [[Fenway Park]] prior to a [[Boston Red Sox|Red Sox]]&ndash;[[Baltimore Orioles|Orioles]] game.<ref>{{cite web|author=Alex McPhillips |url=http://boston.redsox.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070801&content_id=2123890&vkey=news_bos&fext=.jsp&c_id=bos |title=Garnett makes a splash at Fenway|website=Boston Red Sox|publisher=MLB |date= |accessdate=April 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe trade for Garnett had many experts speculating that the Celtics would have a resurgence during the [[2007\u201308 NBA season|2007\u201308 season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/news/kgarnett_traded_celtics.html|publisher=NBA.com|title=Reaction to the Celtics Acquiring Kevin Garnett|accessdate=May 15, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090308024545/http://www.nba.com/news/kgarnett_traded_celtics.html|archive-date=March 8, 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref> The combination of [[Paul Pierce]], [[Ray Allen]], and Garnett were almost automatically nicknamed \"The Big Three\" by the media, after the [[Larry Bird]], [[Kevin McHale (basketball)|Kevin McHale]], and [[Robert Parish]] trio.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.commercialappeal.com/news/2007/oct/15/allen-garnett-pierce-continue-big-3-tradition/|publisher=commercialappeal.com|title=Allen, Garnett, Pierce continue Big 3 tradition|accessdate=May 15, 2010}}</ref> Garnett wore jersey number 5 for the Celtics since his number with the Timberwolves, number 21, was retired by the Celtics, previously worn by [[Bill Sharman]]. He made his Boston debut with a strong performance against the Washington Wizards, with 22 points and 20 rebounds.<ref>Associated Press. (November 2, 2007). \"[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=271102002 Washington Wizards vs. Boston Celtics Recap]\". ESPN. Retrieved on July 18, 2009.</ref> He also led all players in voting for the [[2008 NBA All-Star Game]]. Garnett received 2,399,148 votes, the sixth highest total in NBA All-Star balloting history.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/allstar2008/allstar_starters_080124.html |title=Boston's Kevin Garnett Top Vote-Getter Among All-Stars |publisher=Nba.com |date=January 25, 2008 |accessdate=April 20, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103162351/http://www.nba.com/allstar2008/allstar_starters_080124.html |archive-date=November 3, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> However, Garnett was unable to play due to an [[Abdominal pain|abdominal strain]], and [[Detroit Pistons]] forward [[Rasheed Wallace]] was named to replace him.<ref>[http://www.bostonherald.com/blogs/sports/celtics/index.php/2008/02/10/garnett-out-of-all-star-game-wallace-in/ Garnett out of All-Star Game, Wallace in], ''[[Boston Herald]]'', February 10, 2008.</ref><ref>Steve Bulpett, [http://www.bostonherald.com/sports/basketball/celtics/view.bg?articleid=1072714 No 'Big Ticket' for an All-Star event], ''[[Boston Herald]]'', February 11, 2008.</ref><ref>Marc J. Spears, [http://www.boston.com/sports/basketball/celtics/articles/2008/02/16/rondo_will_have_to_pay_up/?page=2 Rondo will have to pay up], ''[[The Boston Globe]]'', February 16, 2008.</ref> Garnett passed 20,000 points for his career, becoming the 32nd player in NBA history to reach the mark,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/news/garnett20k_080307.html |title=Kevin Garnett Reaches 20,000-Point Plateau |publisher=Nba.com |date=March 9, 2008 |accessdate=April 20, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121102131115/http://www.nba.com/news/garnett20k_080307.html |archive-date=November 2, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> with a [[layup]] in the second quarter against the [[Memphis Grizzlies]] on March 8.<ref>Steve Bulpett, [http://www.bostonherald.com/sports/basketball/celtics/view.bg?articleid=1078957&srvc=celt&position=1 C's go extra milestone \u2013 Numbers come up for Garnett, Allen], ''[[Boston Herald]]'', March 9, 2008.</ref> On April 22, Garnett was named the [[NBA Defensive Player of the Year Award|NBA Defensive Player of the Year]] for the 2007\u201308 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/news/garnett_defensive_080422.html |title=Kevin Garnett Wins Kia Defensive Player of the Year |publisher=Nba.com |date=April 25, 2008 |accessdate=April 20, 2012 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/65arS45Kh?url=http://www.nba.com/news/garnett_defensive_080422.html |archive-date=February 20, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[http://www.nba.com/celtics/playoffs2008/press042208-garnett-defensive-player.html Kevin Garnett Wins NBA Defensive Player of the Year] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080502203755/http://www.nba.com/celtics/playoffs2008/press042208-garnett-defensive-player.html |date=May 2, 2008 }}, ''[[Boston Celtics|Celtics]].com'', April 22, 2008.</ref> It was the only major award a Celtic player had not claimed since the [[History of the Boston Celtics|franchise's foundation]] in 1946.<ref>Marc J. Spears, [http://www.boston.com/sports/basketball/celtics/articles/2008/04/22/garnett_wins_nba_defensive_player_award/ Garnett wins NBA defensive player award], ''[[The Boston Globe]]'', April 22, 2008.</ref> Garnett said it was a team effort which helped him win the award.<ref>Couper Moorhead, [http://www.nba.com/celtics/playoffs2008/sidebar042208-garnett-defensive-player-year.html KG Calls Defensive Player of the Year Award a \"Team Effort\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080501054125/http://www.nba.com/celtics/playoffs2008/sidebar042208-garnett-defensive-player-year.html |date=May 1, 2008 }}, ''[[Boston Celtics|Celtics]].com'', April 22, 2008.</ref> Garnett was also third in [[NBA Most Valuable Player Award|MVP]] voting for the year, behind only [[Kobe Bryant]] and [[Chris Paul]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/news/kobe_mvp_080506.html |title=Kobe Bryant Wins Most Valuable Player Award |publisher=Nba.com |date=May 6, 2008 |accessdate=April 20, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401110138/http://www.nba.com/news/kobe_mvp_080506.html |archive-date=April 1, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Garnett helped the Celtics to their 17th [[NBA Finals|NBA Championship]], with 26 [[Point (basketball)|points]] and 14 [[Rebound (basketball)|rebounds]] in [[2008 NBA Finals#Game 6|Game 6]] of the [[2008 NBA Finals|NBA Finals]]. During that championship season, Garnett and Celtics legend [[Bill Russell]] developed a relationship, which Garnett credited as a major influence in helping him succeed during his first season as a Celtic.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/russellkg_gallery/080305_1.html |publisher=nba.com |title=Bill Russell and Kevin Garnett: March 6, 2008 |accessdate=May 15, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100618073855/http://www.nba.com/russellkg_gallery/080305_1.html |archivedate=June 18, 2010}}</ref> On June 18, 2008, Garnett and Ray Allen appeared on the ''[[Late Show with David Letterman]]'', soon after winning the championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wbztv.com/local/Boston.Celtics.David.2.751236.html |publisher=wbztv.com |title=Garnett, Allen Appear On Letterman |accessdate=May 15, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081004180240/http://wbztv.com/local/Boston.Celtics.David.2.751236.html |archivedate=October 4, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2008\u201309 NBA season|2008\u201309 season]], Garnett started all of the 57 games he was able to suit up for. He averaged 15.8 points, 8.5 rebounds and 2.5 assists. On October 31, 2008, Garnett became the youngest player in [[NBA records|NBA history]] to reach 1,000 career games, at 32 years and 165 days.<ref>[http://scores.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=281031002 Garnett becomes youngest to reach 1,000 games, leads Celtics past Bulls], [[Associated Press]], October 31, 2008.</ref><ref>Frank Dell'Apa, [http://www.boston.com/sports/basketball/celtics/articles/2008/11/01/rondos_deal_is_extended/ Rondo's deal is extended], ''[[The Boston Globe]]'', November 1, 2008.</ref> Garnett earned his twelfth consecutive [[2009 NBA All-Star Game|All-Star Game]] start on February 15, 2009. Following the All-Star Game, during a game against the [[Utah Jazz]], Garnett strained his right knee late in the second quarter. The injury occurred on February 19, 2009, while attempting to go up for an [[Alley-oop (basketball)|alley-oop]].<ref>Associated Press (February 19, 2009). \"[http://espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=290219026 Boston Celtics vs. Utah Jazz Recap]\". ESPN. Retrieved on July 15, 2009.</ref> He was forced to miss the next 14 games. Upon his return from the injury, he averaged 9 points and 4.5 rebounds in four games before being shut down for the season permanently, missing the final 25 games of the regular season, as well as the [[2009 NBA Playoffs|2009 playoffs]] due to a right knee sprain.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.boston.com/sports/basketball/celtics/articles/2009/05/18/comfortable_with_the_long_term_picture/ | work=The Boston Globe | title=Comfortable with the long-term picture | first=Marc J. | last=Spears | date=May 18, 2009}}</ref> Without Garnett, the Celtics advanced to the Eastern Conference semi-finals, but were eliminated by the Orlando Magic.\n\nIn the [[2009\u201310 NBA season|2009\u201310 season]], Garnett and the Celtics, joined by newly signed free agent [[Rasheed Wallace]], struggled with injuries and inconsistency throughout much of the regular season and earned the fourth seed in the Eastern Conference playoffs. Garnett was selected to play in the [[2010 NBA All-Star Game]] (his 13th All-Star Game selection). Despite being written off by nearly every major sports analyst, the Celtics elevated their play and consistency, and dominated opponents much as they did during their 2008 championship run. They eliminated the [[Miami Heat]], [[Cleveland Cavaliers]], and [[Orlando Magic]] to advance to face the [[Los Angeles Lakers]] in the [[2010 NBA Finals]]. In Game 6 against the Cavaliers, Garnett recorded 22 points, 12 rebounds and 3 assists in the series-clinching win.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/boxscores/201005130BOS.html|title=Cleveland Cavaliers at Boston Celtics Box Score, May 13, 2010|publisher=Basketball Reference|date=May 13, 2010|accessdate=January 17, 2020}}</ref> The 2010 Finals went to a decisive seventh game in Los Angeles, where the Celtics led well into the third quarter before the Lakers mounted a comeback and held on for the victory.<ref>{{cite news |first=Greg |last=Beacham |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nba/recap?gid=2010061713 |title=Lakers edge Celtics in Game 7, win 16th title |work=Yahoo! Sports |date=June 18, 2010 |accessdate=December 29, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110805044734/http://sports.yahoo.com/nba/recap?gid=2010061713 |archivedate=August 5, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[2010\u201311 NBA season]], Garnett and the Celtics started strong, winning 23 of their first 26 games. On December 30, 2010, Garnett injured his right knee after he tried to dunk. He missed two weeks with the injury. Garnett returned on January 17, 2011 to face the Orlando Magic.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/g/garneke01/gamelog/2011/ |title=Kevin Garnett 2010-11 Game Log |work=Basketball-Reference.com |accessdate=December 20, 2015}}</ref> The Celtics ended the regular season third in the Eastern Conference behind the [[Chicago Bulls]] and the [[Miami Heat]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sportsofboston.com/2011/04/14/2010-2011-celtics-regular-season-wrap-up/ |title=2010-2011 Celtics Regular Season Wrap-Up |publisher=Sports of Boston |date= |accessdate=August 10, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111129085709/http://sportsofboston.com/2011/04/14/2010-2011-celtics-regular-season-wrap-up/ |archive-date=November 29, 2011 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Garnett averaged under 15 points, under 9 rebounds, and a career low 0.8 blocks per game. After sweeping the [[New York Knicks]] in the first round, they faced the Heat in the semi-finals. After losing the first two games of the series, Garnett's playoff high 28 points helped the Celtics take Game 3. However, the Heat won the next two games, winning the series 4\u20131.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/playoffs/2011/eastseries6/ |title=Celtics vs. Heat &#124; Eastern Conference Semi-Finals &#124; 2011 NBA Playoffs |publisher=NBA.com |date= |accessdate=August 10, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170915141844/http://www.nba.com/playoffs/2011/eastseries6/ |archive-date=September 15, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn the lockout shortened [[2011\u201312 NBA season]], Garnett and the Celtics started off slowly, being below .500 with a 15\u201317 record by the All-Star break. Garnett was not selected for the All-Star game for the first time in 11 years. After, however, Boston quickly became one of the best teams in the league, finishing the second half of the season with a 24\u201310 record, entering the playoffs as the fourth seed in the Eastern Conference with a 39\u201327 record. Boston made a deep run in the playoffs, going all the way to the Eastern Conference Finals. They faced the Atlanta Hawks in the first round, defeating them in six games. Boston then defeated the Philadelphia 76ers after a challenging seven-game series. Boston made the Eastern Conference Finals for the third time in five years, and faced another superstar trio in Chris Bosh, Dwyane Wade and LeBron James of the Miami Heat. The Celtics lost the first two games, but came back strong to win the next three games. However, the Heat were too strong in Games 6 and 7, defeating the Celtics 4\u20133. Garnett found a resurgence in the playoffs, averaging 19.2 points, 10.3 rebounds and 1.4 blocks per game.\n\nOn June 30, 2012, Garnett agreed to a three-year contract extension with the Celtics worth an estimated $34 million.<ref>{{cite news|first=Gary |last=Washburn |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/basketball/celtics/extras/celtics_blog/2012/06/garnett_agrees.html |title=Garnett agrees to an extension with Celtics |newspaper=The Boston Globe |date=June 30, 2012 |accessdate=June 30, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/boston/nba/story/_/id/8115843/boston-celtics-kevin-garnett-returning-team-sources-say |title=Sources: Kevin Garnett returning |publisher=ESPN |date=June 30, 2012 |accessdate=June 30, 2012}}</ref> On January 17, 2013, it was announced that Garnett had been voted to start in the 2013 All-Star Game in Houston.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/2013/news/01/17/all-star-2013-starters-announced/index.html |title=Top vote-getter Kobe earns record 15th straight All-Star trip |access-date=February 15, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130315184841/http://www.nba.com/2013/news/01/17/all-star-2013-starters-announced/index.html |archive-date=March 15, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On February 7, 2013, Garnett recorded his 25,000th point in a 116\u201395 victory over the Los Angeles Lakers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/games/20130207/LALBOS/gameinfo.html |title=Lakers at Celtics |access-date=February 8, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171107004301/http://www.nba.com/games/20130207/LALBOS/gameinfo.html |archive-date=November 7, 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/video/clip?id=8928229|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130208101902/http://espn.go.com/video/clip?id=8928229|url-status=dead|title=Garnett Reaches 25,000 Points In Celtics' Win|archivedate=February 8, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Brooklyn Nets (2013\u20132015)===\nOn June 27, 2013, the day of the [[2013 NBA draft|NBA draft]], the Boston Celtics and the [[Brooklyn Nets]] reached a deal to trade Garnett, [[Paul Pierce]] and [[Jason Terry]] for future first-round picks in the [[2014 NBA draft|2014]], 2016, and 2018 drafts, as well as [[Kris Humphries]], [[Gerald Wallace]], [[Kris Joseph]], [[MarShon Brooks]] and [[Keith Bogans]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/9429958/sources-brooklyn-nets-seek-trade-boston-celtics-kevin-garnett-paul-pierce|title=Nets, Celtics work out blockbuster|publisher=ESPN|date=June 28, 2013|accessdate=June 28, 2013}}</ref> The deal was finally completed on July 12, with Brooklyn also receiving [[D. J. White]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/nets/news/nets-acquire-nba-champions-kevin-garnett-paul-pierce-and-jason-terry|title=Nets Acquire NBA Champions Kevin Garnett, Paul Pierce and Jason Terry|work=NBA.com|publisher=Turner Sports Interactive, Inc.|date=July 12, 2013|accessdate=July 14, 2013}}</ref> Garnett chose to wear number 2 to honor his former Minnesota Timberwolves teammate [[Malik Sealy]].<ref name=netsjersey>{{cite news|title=Kevin Garnett, Paul Pierce, Jason Terry Brooklyn Nets Jerseys Already For Sale|url=http://nesn.com/2013/07/kevin-garnett-paul-pierce-jason-terry-brooklyn-nets-jerseys-already-for-sale-photo/|accessdate=July 14, 2013|work=NESN.com|date=July 12, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/new-york/brooklyn-nets/post/_/id/11811/kevin-garnett-to-wear-no-2-to-honor-malik-sealy|title=Garnett to wear No. 2 to honor Sealy|publisher=ESPN.com|date=July 18, 2013|accessdate=July 18, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn December 13, 2013, Garnett surpassed 14,000 career rebounds, becoming only the tenth player in NBA history to do so. In reaching the milestone, Garnett also joined [[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar]] and [[Karl Malone]] as the only players to reach 25,000 points, 14,000 rebounds and 5,000 assists. He reached the milestone in the third quarter of a 103\u201399 road loss to the [[Detroit Pistons]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/games/20131213/BKNDET/gameinfo.html |title=Notebook: Pistons 103, Nets 99 |access-date=December 15, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131215141106/http://www.nba.com/games/20131213/BKNDET/gameinfo.html |archive-date=December 15, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The Nets cherished Garnett's leadership and passion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2015/12/19/nets-have-nothing-but-good-things-to-say-about-kevin-garnett/|title=Nets have nothing but good things to say about Kevin Garnett|first=Brian|last=Lewis|date=December 20, 2015}}</ref> Despite boasting a starting line-up of [[Deron Williams]], [[Joe Johnson (basketball)|Joe Johnson]], [[Brook Lopez]], Paul Pierce, and Garnett, the Nets were unable to advance past the second round of the playoffs, while Garnett finished his 19th NBA season with career low averages of 6.5 points and 6.6 rebounds per game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/g/garneke01/gamelog/2014/|title=Kevin Garnett 2013-14 Game Log|website=Basketball-Reference.com}}</ref>\n\nOn November 1, 2014, Garnett had arguably his best game for the Nets as he recorded 18 points and 14 rebounds in 35 minutes of action in the Nets' 102\u201390 win over the Detroit Pistons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/blog/new-york/brooklyn-nets/post/_/id/21011/kevin-garnett-has-best-game-with-brooklyn|title=Kevin Garnett has best game with Brooklyn|date=November 2, 2014|website=ESPN.com}}</ref> Six days later, he recorded five rebounds in a 110\u201399 win over the New York Knicks and by doing so, passed [[Walt Bellamy]] for ninth place on the all-time rebounding list.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20141107/NYKBKN/gameinfo.html|title=Nets rout Knicks in 1st all-NY matchup of season|access-date=November 8, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109210317/http://www.nba.com/games/20141107/NYKBKN/gameinfo.html|archive-date=November 9, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Return to Minnesota (2015\u20132016)===\n[[File:KGsReturnToMN2015.JPG|thumb|Garnett's first game back with the Timberwolves in 2015.]]\nOn February 19, 2015, Garnett agreed to waive his no-trade clause in order to be traded back to Minnesota in exchange for [[Thaddeus Young]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nba.com/timberwolves/wolves-acquire-forward-kevin-garnett|title=Wolves Acquire Forward Kevin Garnett|work=NBA.com|date=February 19, 2015|accessdate=February 19, 2015}}</ref> Six days later, he made his return for the Timberwolves against the Washington Wizards at the [[Target Center]], recording five points on 2-of-7 shooting with eight rebounds and two blocks in 19 minutes in his first game for Minnesota since 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20150225/WASMIN/gameinfo.html|title=Kevin Garnett a winner in emotional return to Wolves|work=NBA.com|date=February 25, 2015|accessdate=February 25, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150225011312/http://www.nba.com/games/20150225/WASMIN/gameinfo.html|archive-date=February 25, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> He appeared in just five games for the Timberwolves in 2014\u201315, before sitting out the team's final 21 games of the season due to a nagging knee injury.<ref>{{cite news|last=Faklis|first=Tim|url=http://www.awolfamongwolves.com/2015/06/2014-15-roster-review-kevin-garnett/|title=2014-15 Roster Review: Kevin Garnett|work=awolfamongwolves.com|date=June 21, 2015|accessdate=January 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn July 11, 2015, Garnett re-signed with the Timberwolves to a two-year deal.<ref>{{cite web|title=Timberwolves Re-Sign Forward Kevin Garnett|url=http://www.nba.com/timberwolves/timberwolves-re-sign-forward-kevin-garnett|work=NBA.com|date=July 11, 2015|accessdate=July 13, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Timberwolves bring back Kevin Garnett, sign Karl-Anthony Towns|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/13214285/kevin-garnett-karl-anthony-towns-sign-minnesota-timberwolves|work=ESPN.com|date=July 7, 2015|accessdate=July 7, 2015}}</ref> On November 15, 2015, against the Memphis Grizzlies, Garnett became the fifth player in NBA history to play at least 50,000 minutes, joining [[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar]], [[Karl Malone]], [[Jason Kidd]] and [[Elvin Hayes]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Conley, Green lead Grizzlies over Timberwolves 114-106|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20151115/MEMMIN/gameinfo.html|work=NBA.com|date=November 15, 2015|accessdate=November 15, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151115220152/http://www.nba.com/games/20151115/MEMMIN/gameinfo.html|archive-date=November 15, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> On December 1, against the Orlando Magic, Garnett surpassed Kidd (50,110) for third on the NBA's career minutes list.<ref>{{cite web|title=Magic hold off late charge from Wolves for 4th straight win|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20151201/ORLMIN/gameinfo.html|work=NBA.com|date=December 1, 2015|accessdate=December 1, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151205234829/http://www.nba.com/games/20151201/ORLMIN/gameinfo.html|archive-date=December 5, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> Four days later, in a loss to the Portland Trail Blazers, he became the 15th player in NBA history to surpass 26,000 career points.<ref>{{cite web|title=Blazers come back from 17 down again to beat Wolves|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20151205/PORMIN/gameinfo.html|work=NBA.com|date=December 5, 2015|accessdate=December 5, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151206232234/http://www.nba.com/games/20151205/PORMIN/gameinfo.html|archive-date=December 6, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> On December 11, Garnett passed Malone as the NBA's all-time leader in defensive rebounds during Minnesota's 111\u2013108 overtime loss to the Denver Nuggets. He finished the game with four defensive boards to give him 11,409 for his career, three ahead of Malone.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kevin Garnett passes Karl Malone as NBA's all-time def. rebound leader|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/14347180/kevin-garnett-minnesota-timberwolves-becomes-nba-all-defensive-rebound-leader|work=ESPN.com|date=December 11, 2015|accessdate=December 11, 2015}}</ref> Garnett appeared in 38 of the team's first 45 games of the season before missing the entire second half of the season with a right knee injury, the same knee that kept him out of 25 games in 2008\u201309 when he was playing for Boston, as well as much of his post-trade time in Minnesota during the 2014\u201315 season.<ref>{{cite web|last=Schmidt|first=Nolan|title=Will the Timberwolves\u2019 Kevin Garnett play again?|url=http://dunkingwithwolves.com/2016/03/13/will-timberwolves-kevin-garnett-play/|work=dunkingwithwolves.com|date=March 13, 2016|accessdate=April 13, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn September 23, 2016, Garnett announced his retirement after 21 seasons in the NBA.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kevin Garnett Announces Retirement|url=http://www.nba.com/timberwolves/kevin-garnett-announces-retirement|website=NBA.com|date=September 23, 2016|accessdate=September 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Krawczynski |first1=Jon |title=Garnett says 'farewell' to the NBA after 21 seasons |url=http://www.nba.com/2016/news/09/23/kevin-garnett-plans-to-retire-after-21-seasons.ap/index.html |website=NBA.com |date=September 23, 2016 |accessdate=September 24, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160924062439/http://www.nba.com/2016/news/09/23/kevin-garnett-plans-to-retire-after-21-seasons.ap/index.html |archivedate=September 24, 2016}}</ref> While Garnett did express interest in playing for one more season with the Timberwolves, primarily with the goal in helping the team make it to the playoffs again with its promising young players and new head coach, he also told the team's owner that he wasn't sure that his knees would hold up for one more season.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bondy|first1=Stefan|title=Kevin Garnett wants to return for a 22nd NBA season, but told T-Wolves owner 'I don't know if I can'|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/basketball/kevin-garnett-told-t-wolves-owner-22nd-season-article-1.2714186|website=NYDailyNews.com|date=July 16, 2016|accessdate=September 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==National team career==\nIn the [[2000 Summer Olympics]], Garnett won a [[gold medal]] as a member of the [[United States men's national basketball team|United States national team]]. In his first and only FIBA tournament, Garnett averaged 10.8 points, 9.1 rebounds and 2.1 assists per game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.fiba.com/pages/eng/fa/p/rpp//q/kevin%20garnett/pid//_//players.html|title=archive.fiba.com: Players}}</ref>\n\n==Post-playing career==\nIn October 2016, Garnett joined the crew on [[TNT (U.S. TV network)|TNT]]'s ''[[Inside the NBA]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Moore|first=Matt|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nba/news/kevin-garnett-is-headed-to-tnts-inside-the-nba/|title=Kevin Garnett is headed to TNT's 'Inside the NBA'|work=CBSSports.com|date=October 27, 2016|accessdate=October 28, 2016}}</ref> The following month, he became the host of his own segment, ''Area 21''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Stensaas|first=Brian|url=http://www.startribune.com/kevin-garnett-brings-area-21-to-nba-on-tnt-with-the-cuss-button/399961321/|title=Kevin Garnett brings 'Area 21' to NBA on TNT \u2013 with the cuss button|work=StarTribune.com|date=November 4, 2016|accessdate=November 17, 2016}}</ref> In January 2017, Garnett joined the [[Los Angeles Clippers]] as a consultant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/article/2017/01/10/kevin-garnett-clippers-consultant|title=Clippers hire Kevin Garnett as team consultant|work=NBA.com|date=January 10, 2017|accessdate=January 11, 2017}}</ref> He also consulted with the [[Milwaukee Bucks]] during the 2016\u201317 season.<ref>{{cite web|last=Metallinos|first=Nick|url=http://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/18700033/nba-great-kevin-garnett-gives-seal-approval-milwaukee-bucks-australian-nba-star-thon-maker-saying-chance-special|title=Kevin Garnett says Thon Maker has 'a chance to be special'|work=ESPN.com|date=February 16, 2017|accessdate=May 2, 2017}}</ref>\n===''Uncut Gems''===\n{{main|Uncut Gems}}\n{{quote box\n| quote = \"You realize how hard he worked in acting\u2014he must've worked three times as hard on the court\"\n| author =\u2014''[[Uncut Gems]]'' producer Sebastian Bear-McClard on Garnett<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theringer.com/movies/2019/12/13/21015844/uncut-gems-kevin-garnett-casting-adam-sandler-safdie-brothers|title=How Kevin Garnett Landed in \u2018Uncut Gems\u2019|first=Alan|last=Siegel|date=December 13, 2019|website=The Ringer}}</ref>\n| source = \n| align = leftack\n| width = 15%\n}}\nGarnett plays a fictionalized version of himself in the 2019 [[crime film|crime]] [[thriller film]] ''[[Uncut Gems]]'', directed by the [[Safdie brothers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.masslive.com/celtics/2019/09/kevin-garnett-starring-in-uncut-gems-movie-where-adam-sandler-plays-jewelry-dealer-who-makes-bad-boston-celtics-bets.html|title=Kevin Garnett starring in 'Uncut Gems,' movie where Adam Sandler plays jewelry dealer who makes bad Boston Celtics bets|last1=O'Malley|first1=Nick|date=24 September 2019|website=masslive.com|language=en|accessdate=September 24, 2019}}</ref> The movie is set in 2012 and revolves around an [[2012 NBA playoffs#(4)%20Boston%20Celtics%20vs%20(8)%20Philadelphia%2076ers|Eastern Conference Semifinals series]] from that year between the Boston Celtics and Philadelphia 76ers. Garnett makes a trip from Philadelphia to a jewelry store owned by [[Adam Sandler]]'s character Howard Ratner in [[Diamond District, Manhattan|New York's Diamond District]] and takes a liking to an [[Welo opal|Ethiopian opal]] which Ratner shows him; this leads to events that eventually spiral into chaos as the movie goes on. \n\nGarnett's performance received very positive reviews from critics.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/12/kevin-garnett-in-uncut-gems-are-you-ready.html|title=Are You Ready for Kevin Garnett, the Actor?|last=Harris|first=Hunter|date=2019-12-13|website=Vulture|language=en-us|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theringer.com/movies/2019/12/13/21015844/uncut-gems-kevin-garnett-casting-adam-sandler-safdie-brothers|title=How Kevin Garnett Landed in \u2018Uncut Gems\u2019|last=Siegel|first=Alan|date=2019-12-13|website=The Ringer|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> The Safdie brothers arrived at Garnett after a series of rewrites based on player availability. Their choices before Garnett included [[Amar'e Stoudemire]] (denied to cut his hair to the time period),<ref name=\":0\" /> [[Kobe Bryant]] (his representation said he wanted to direct, not act, though Bryant denied any knowledge of the project)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/nba/story/_/id/28281521/how-kevin-garnett-teamed-adam-sandler-uncut-gems|title=Lowe: How Kevin Garnett teamed up with Adam Sandler in 'Uncut Gems'|date=2019-12-13|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> and [[Joel Embiid]] (his schedule made it impossible to film).<ref name=\":0\" /> Garnett was one of the first retired athletes they approached. Garnett later said the process of filming \"felt special, but you didn\u2019t know it.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vulture.com/2019/12/kevin-garnett-julia-fox-uncut-gems-interview.html|title=Kevin Garnett and Julia Fox on Gambling, Superstitions, and Uncut Gems|last=Harris|first=Hunter|date=2019-12-13|website=Vulture|language=en-us|access-date=2019-12-16}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nGarnett wore clothing branded as \"OBF\", standing for Official Block Family. The name came from what he called his close group of friends from Beachwood Drive in Mauldin, South Carolina. He brought OBF members to live with him in his Minnesota home, and let some on board some team's charter flights during road trips.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.oocities.org/garnetttribute/obf.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=December 17, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160213101705/http://www.oocities.org/garnetttribute/obf.html |archive-date=February 13, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"sportsonearth1\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/nothing-garnett-162577|title=Nothing But Garnett|first=Allison Samuels On 2/13/00 at 7:00 PM|last=EST|date=February 13, 2000|website=Newsweek}}</ref> He met [[Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis]], the Grammy-winning record producers for [[Janet Jackson]] and [[Boyz II Men]], early in his career in Minnesota and considers them as mentors.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n\nIn July 2004, Garnett married his longtime girlfriend Brandi Padilla during a private ceremony in [[California]]. Due to the wedding, Garnett did not take part in the [[Athens 2004|Athens Olympic Games]].<ref>[[Marc Stein (reporter)|Marc Stein]] [http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/columns/story?columnist=stein_marc&id=1812395 Team USA carousel continues], ''[[ESPN]]'', April 29, 2004.</ref> The couple has two daughters. On July 12, 2018, Garnett's wife filed for divorce, asking for custody of the children.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.tmz.com/2018/07/12/kevin-garnett-getting-divorced-wife-brandi/|title=NBA Legend Kevin Garnett and Wife Getting Divorced|work=TMZ|access-date=July 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://theblast.com/kevin-garnett-kg-wife-split/|title=Kevin Garnett's Wife Files for Divorce, She Wants Custody of Kids|date=July 12, 2018|work=The Blast|access-date=July 13, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> Garnett is the half-brother of former basketball player [[Louis McCullough]]. Another professional basketball player, former [[Los Angeles Lakers|Los Angeles Laker]] [[Shammond Williams]], is his cousin.<ref>{{cite web|last=Nunez|first=Tammy|url=http://www.nola.com/tulane/index.ssf/2013/07/tulane_names_shammond_williams.html |title=Tulane names Shammond Williams, cousin of Kevin Garnett, as its new assistant basketball coach |work=NOLA.com |date=July 17, 2013 |accessdate=December 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\nHis nicknames include \"The Big Ticket\", \"KG\", \"The Kid\" and formerly \"The Franchise\" (after being known as the [[Minnesota Timberwolves]]' franchise player).<ref name=\"nbabio\" /> Before games, he mentally prepares himself by banging his head against a padded basketball stanchion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/04/18/sports/basketball/18playoffs.html?_r=0|title=N.B.A. Playoffs May Pivot on Health of Best Teams|work=New York Times|author=Jonathan Abrams|date=April 17, 2009|accessdate=February 23, 2013}}</ref> Although Garnett is officially listed as {{height|ft=6|in=11}} by the NBA, he is widely accepted to be at least {{height|ft=7}} tall.<ref>Peter Stringer, [http://www.nba.com/celtics/news/blog/post-ups.html Postgame Wrap Up \u2013 KG or K9?], ''Celtics.com'', March 28, 2008.</ref><ref>Shira Springer, [http://www.boston.com/sports/basketball/celtics/extras/celtics_blog/2007/07/more_details_on.html Garnett deal in place], ''[[The Boston Globe]]'', July 30, 2007.</ref> During the [[2007 NBA All-Star Game]], Garnett admitted in an interview with [[Craig Sager]] to be \"6 ft 11 in and some quarters\" tall.<ref>{{YouTube|PRIm4_yvocc|Kevin Garnett Craig Sager Interview 2007 All Star Game}}</ref> Measurements from the [[1995 NBA draft]] indicated that Garnett, who was 19 years old at the time, was {{height|ft=6|in=11}} tall barefoot.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.draftexpress.com/nba-pre-draft-measurements/?year=1995&sort2=ASC&draft=100&sort= |title=Pre Draft Measurements |publisher=DraftExpress |date= |accessdate=December 29, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151019182748/http://www.draftexpress.com/nba-pre-draft-measurements/?year=1995&sort2=ASC&draft=100&sort= |archivedate=October 19, 2015}}</ref> In 1997, Garnett was measured by the Minnesota Timberwolves training staff to be {{height|ft=7|in=1}} tall in his basketball shoes.<ref>\"Missed Workouts Put Garnett 'A Little Behind'\", ''St. Paul Pioneer Press'', October 3, 1997. Page 7E.</ref> In December 2011, Garnett agreed to become a limited shareholder of American-owned Italian [[Serie A]] [[Association football|football]] team [[A.S. Roma]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/boston/nba/story/_/id/7403380/boston-celtics-kevin-garnett-buy-limited-share-roma |title=Boston Celtics' Kevin Garnett to buy limited share of Roma |publisher=Espn.go.com |date=December 30, 2011 |accessdate=April 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==NBA career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend|champion=y|leader=y}}\n\n===Regular season===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|1995}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[1995\u201396 Minnesota Timberwolves season|Minnesota]]\n| 80 || 43 || 28.7 || .491 || .286 || .705 || 6.3 || 1.8 || 1.1 || 1.6 || 10.4\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|1996}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[1996\u201397 Minnesota Timberwolves season|Minnesota]]\n| 77 || 77 || 38.9 || .499 || .286 || .754 || 8.0 || 3.1 || 1.4 || 2.1 || 17.0\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|1997}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[1997\u201398 Minnesota Timberwolves season|Minnesota]]\n| style=\"background:#cfecec;\"| '''82'''* || style=\"background:#cfecec;\"| '''82'''* || 39.3 || .491 || .188 || .738 || 9.6 || 4.2 || '''1.7''' || 1.8 || 18.5\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|1998}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[1998\u201399 Minnesota Timberwolves season|Minnesota]]\n| 47 || 47 || 37.9 || .460 || .286 || .704 || 10.4 || 4.3 || '''1.7''' || 1.8 || 20.8\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|1999|trunc=y}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[1999\u20132000 Minnesota Timberwolves season|Minnesota]]\n| 81 || 81 || 40.0 || .497 || '''.370''' || .765 || 11.8 || 5.0 || 1.5 || 1.6 || 22.9\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|2000}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2000\u201301 Minnesota Timberwolves season|Minnesota]]\n| 81 || 81 || 39.5 || .477 || .288 || .764 || 11.4 || 5.0 || 1.4 || 1.8 || 22.0\n|-\n| sty